revision.text:
'''Dilutive securities''' are financial instruments like [[stock options]], [[warrant (finance)|warrants]], [[convertible bonds]], etc. which increases the number of [[common stock]], if exercised. It reduces the basic EPS ([[earnings per share]]).<ref name="KiesoWeygandt2010">{{cite book|author1=Donald E. Kieso|author2=Jerry J. Weygandt|author3=Terry D. Warfield|title=Intermediate Accounting: IFRS Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_tmMkC5DNuAC&pg=PA822|date=4 October 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-61631-4|pages=822}}</ref> Only if the [[diluted EPS]] is less than the [[basic EPS]] then it is called dilutive securities.<ref name="BrighamDaves2012">{{cite book|author1=Eugene F. Brigham|author2=Phillip R. Daves|title=Intermediate Financial Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=joxlJpPGgXIC&pg=PA781|date=24 February 2012|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=1-111-53026-2|pages=781–}}</ref>

